has been experiencing some perianal itching. His perineum is examined (Image). The patient does not know how long this dark area has been there and he is not sexually active.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Melanoma","Perianal abscess","Thrombosed haemorrhoid","Lichen planus","HPV infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a flattened, darkly pigmented lesion in the perianal region. It is asymmetrical in colour, has irregular borders and some colour variations. It is likely to have grown over time but given the location, it would be difficult for the patient to know. This is highly suspicious for a melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanoma \u003C/strong\u003Eis a cancer of the melanocytes, presenting as an irregularly pigmented lesion.  Unfortunately, there has been trend in rise in prevalence of melanoma in Australia.  Clinicians can utilise the \u0027ABCDE\u0027 acronym to help distinguish melanoma from a benign naevi.  The acronym stands for: Asymmetry of colour and shape, Border irregularity, Colour variation \u0026amp; change, Different, Evolving over time.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerianal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is a localised collection of pus associated with pain, discharge and other signs of systemic infection. It does not explain the pigmented lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombosed haemorrhoid\u003C/strong\u003E may have similar colour to the lesion shown but should have a history of pain, swelling or lump and bleeding after defaecation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen planus \u003C/strong\u003Eis an an inflammatory condition that often presents with itch.  It can involve skin, mucosa, nail and hair.  It can present with violaeous-erythematous colored rash and can mimic presentation seen above in the photo.  However, it does not have brown-pigment network which would been in a melanoma when viewed using a dermatoscope.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHPV infection\u003C/strong\u003E causes cutaneous-mucosal warts which often have papillomatous or verrucous appearance.  \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Melanoma must be suspected in pigmented lesions, likelihood can be determined using the acronym ABCDE"],"references":["DermNet. Melanoma [Internet]. UK; 2022 [cited 2022 Nov 15]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/melanoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17286"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1038"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18814"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18814"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b2528371-0927-4636-b082-b0713f514762.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b2528371-0927-4636-b082-b0713f514762.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17286"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-10T20:34:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-01-10T20:34:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1038"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31497"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","